Comments are off because it was too distracting for my ADHD.
To answer some questions...
The fence is up! 
Yes! We know gators can climb fences.
No! We are not calling the trappers. There are alligators in every body of water in Florida and we just learn to respect nature. We don't think this guy was a nuisance. The glass door is very reflective and it probably just saw its own reflection. It's mating season after all.
Yes! Pinto is safe and not allowed outside without supervision but a guy needs to pee and poop. 
The leash is to prevent him from running after every scent because he is a Beagle. They hunt! 
We live here because it's beautiful and we love it! Gators and all.
Believe it or not, this is not uncommon in Florida. Took us a while to get used to it too. 
We watch our kids and pets and stay away from the water's edge. 
Please be kind! Just because someone doesn't understand how other people live, it doesn't give them the right to judge from a short video. 
It's just a funny video. Enjoy it!!!

On May 1, 1962, the first Target discount department store opened in a suburb of Minneapolis. So that means today is Targetâs 60th birthday!

Unlike so many of the chain stores of that era that have failed, Target continues to thrive, and the spirit of innovation that has given it an edge is on display at the store you see here. 

This is one of my favorite examples of adaptive reuse. This âsmall formatâ Target, at 3031 SE Powell Blvd. in southeast Portland, Oregon, is retro but not vintage. It opened in 2018, taking over the site of an AMF Pro 300 bowling alley. The closing of the bowling alley was traumatic, with many bemoaning the landlordâs choice to hand over the keys to Target. As somebody who has witnessed the destruction of several cherished bowling alleys, I know that pain. 

But Target simply didnât move in and erase any trace of the former occupant. They embraced the history of the site, preserving the look of the original sign, which of course said BOWL, and adding three bollards to the entrance in the form of gigantic bowling balls. 

Whatâs more, Target kept the form of the  #googie canopy entrance, ensuring that a visit to this store is thrilling, even if like me during my visit a year ago tomorrow, you have no plans to shop. 

Itâs interesting that Target went into business about the time this bowling alley opened, making this a somewhat serendipitous location. 

The way Target handled this location is a vivid reminder of how a 60-year-old business can remain so fresh and relevant today. 

Well done, @target, and happy birthday! #retrologist

The area often looks peaceful from the air but the lack of people during the countyâs stay-at-home order has added a surreal feeling to the picturesque Southern California landscape.
